02 Nov 2015 00:04






There's a lot of elements in here that I normally do not like. I feel like this just escaped being too intentionally dense with the meme/antimeme business. The thing where an author throws a whole bunch of complicated logic-puzzly stuff is fast becoming a hallmark of this particular subject, much like it was with time fuckery when that was all the rage about a year ago or so. I would ask future writers in this particular sandbox to tread with caution, because it's a very fine line between genuine thought provocation and inking bullshit all over the place like some sort of bad writing squid.

I'm also not generally a fan of the  as a device. In this instance, I think it's mostly warranted given the subject matter, but it still grates a little bit every time I see it.

Those things said, the core concept was one that was cool enough that I finished reading and went , and it felt enough like a story that it kept me interested enough to wade through some of the slower parts. Unlike a lot of other people, I enjoy the idea that ghosts are a real thing in the Foundationverse. And so of course, this being the case, one's service to the Foundation does not end with death.

Craftsmanship, preservation of immersion and just plain entertainment count for a lot with me, and so I enjoyed this. I can see where others may not have, but for me personally, it worked pretty well.







